                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d428">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Manchuria/1500: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Dairen</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Turner</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dairen</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-02-23T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >February 23, 1938—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 23—8:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I am informed in confidence by my German colleague that Hitler’s decision to
                    recognize Manchukuo comes as a surprise to him and to Knoll, Reich trade
                    representative in Hsinking, and is contrary to their recommendations. He hazards
                    the opinion that the German Foreign Office is equally taken by surprise.</p>
                <p>By mail to Tokyo, Peiping and Mukden.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Turner</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
